"# Final Project Specification\n\nThis document consolidates the Original Specification and feedback from Architecture, Security, and QA reviews into a single, actionable engineering blueprint. It resolves conflicts, prioritizes production reliability, security, maintainability, and developer experience, and makes explicit architectural and operational decisions required to implement the MVP safely and reliably.\n\nKey prioritized design goals (in order)\n- Production reliability and operational clarity\n- Security (data isolation, secrets, auth/session controls)\n- Maintainability and testability\n- Developer experience and predictable operational costs\n\n---\n\n## Project Overview\n\nAI-powered movie production platform (web + tablet responsive) to centralize pre-production workflows for film studios. MVP features include project lifecycle, script management and parsing, people management, shooting schedules with optimization and conflict detection, budgeting & cost tracking, locations (map integration), asset versioning, basic post tasks, collaboration (comments/approvals/notifications), dashboards, and AI assistance (hosted LLM + deterministic modules). Single-tenant logical isolation per studio is required; operational model clarified below.\n\nCore runtime choices reaffirmed: React + TypeScript frontend (Vercel), Node.js TypeScript backend, Postgres-based relational store (Supabase or managed Postgres), background workers for heavy jobs, hosted LLM provider(s) behind an AI gateway, CDN-backed asset storage.\n\n---\n\n## Final Architecture Decisions\n\n1. Tenancy and Data Isolation (resolved)\n   - Default deployment: shared Postgres (single DB) with strict org-scoping + DB Row-Level Security (RLS) and API-layer enforcement. This is the common, cost-effective default for the MVP.\n   - Per-org strong isolation option: support provisioning separate DB instances and separate storage buckets per org for tenants that require stricter isolation/residency or contractual guarantees. Provisioning is automated via IaC (Terraform modules) and an Org Provisioner service. The platform will support both modes; tenancy mode chosen at org onboarding.\n   - Operational controls for shared-DB:\n     - Hardened RLS policies, exhaustive automated tests (RLS test suite) and CI gating.\n     - Tenant lifecycle automation (provision/deprovision) and runbook for tenant isolation incidents.\n\n2. Backups, Erase, and Legal Holds (resolved)\n   - Backups: daily logical backups for shared DB; for per-tenant DBs, backups at DB instance level. Backups tagged with metadata (timestamp, region, tenant scope).\n   - Erase/GDPR: Implement an erase workflow:\n     - For shared DB: maintain per-tenant exportable snapshots and, where required, run targeted delete plus issuance of a backup restore & scrub workflow. If irreversible deletion from backups required by contract, migrate tenant to isolated DB and purge backups for that DB, or use per-tenant DB from the outset.\n     - For high-assurance deletion/ legal-hold: use per-tenant DBs/buckets.\n   - Retention: default retention configurable per-org (default 365 days for project data). Audit logs retention configured separately (immutable storage with retention policy).\n   - Documented RTO/RPO targets and restore playbooks (see Acceptance Criteria).\n\n3. Asset Upload and Processing (resolved)\n   - Client uploads use direct-to-storage signed URLs (pre-signed S3 or Supabase equivalent). No large uploads handled by serverless functions directly.\n   - Virus/malware scan at ingest (cloud provider scanning or ClamAV in worker).\n   - Processing pipeline (thumbnail generation, PDF parsing, OCR) runs in isolated worker containers with resource limits, enqueued via durable queue. Processed artifacts stored in a CDN-enabled storage bucket.\n   - File size limits:\n     - Scripts: max 20 MB for synchronous parse acceptance (MVP); larger scripts accepted via async flow with explicit progress and storage.\n     - Other assets: up to 200 MB with resumable uploads (S3 multipart/tus). VFX/large media deferred to external specialized storage.\n\n4. AI / LLM Gateway and Controls (resolved)\n   - All calls to externally hosted LLMs go through a centralized AI Gateway service that:\n     - Enforces per-org & per-user quotas and token/execution caps.\n     - Logs cost and usage per-call and emits metrics for billing & alerts.\n     - Applies prompt templates, sanitization, PII redaction (configurable per org), provenance metadata, caching, and deterministic fallbacks.\n     - Supports an opt-out per org (no external LLM; use on-prem or deterministic modules).\n     - Provides synchronous endpoints for low-latency tasks (summaries) with timeouts and asynchronous job endpoints for heavy tasks (optimize, large reports).\n   - Caching: results for deterministic/ idempotent AI outputs (script summaries, previously generated reports) cached for configurable TTL; cache keyed by input hash + prompt_template_id + model_version.\n   - Safety: mandatory provenance metadata in AI responses (prompt template id, model id, token usage, timestamp), and UI shows provenance + \"confidence\" / fallback hint. User feedback mechanism for AI outputs.\n\n5. Real-time Collaboration & Concurrency (resolved)\n   - Realtime transport: evaluate supabase-realtime + presence for MVP; if scaling limits observed, replace with Ably/Pusher/Redis PubSub. Implementation choice is pluggable.\n   - Concurrency model for schedules:\n     - Per-entity optimistic concurrency as baseline (version_token/ETag). Mutating endpoints require version_token; updates failing version mismatch return 409 with current state.\n     - Per-item (row) advisory locks for drag/drop critical operations: API supports lock/lease endpoints (e.g., acquireLock(entityId, ttl)) to present lease-based locking UI when appropriate.\n     - For heavy collaborative editing expectations (multiple simultaneous fine-grained edits), roadmap to CRDT/OT approach; not required for MVP.\n   - Presence and live deltas: presence channels and delta updates for schedule items, comments, notifications to meet <2s in-session propagation.\n\n6. Background Jobs and Worker Guarantees (resolved)\n   - Durable queue with DLQ and visibility/ retry (recommended: Redis + BullMQ for rapid MVP or cloud tasks (SQS/Cloud Tasks) for ops simplicity). Workers are idempotent, carry trace IDs and job provenance, and emit metrics.\n   - Job semantics: idempotency keys on enqueued jobs, exponential backoffs, DLQ for persistent failures, and admin visibility/ retry capability.\n   - Job types: script parsing, PDF processing, optimization (CP-SAT microservice calls), batch AI reports, exports (PDF generation), thumbnails/transcodes.\n\n7. Observability and Tracing (resolved)\n   - OpenTelemetry across frontend (browser traces for user flows), API, workers, and optimization microservice. All external LLM/3rd party calls are traced and carry correlation IDs (generated at request entry).\n   - Sentry for errors, Prometheus/Grafana or hosted metrics for metrics and dashboards, and alerting (PagerDuty/Slack) mapped to SLO/SLA thresholds.\n   - Logging policy: structured logs (JSON) with sensitive fields redacted and audit logs stored in append-only storage.\n\n8. Secrets Management (resolved)\n   - Use a managed secrets store (AWS Secrets Manager, GCP Secret Manager, or HashiCorp Vault) for per-environment and per-org secrets.\n   - Integration tokens stored encrypted at rest using envelope encryption (KMS). Access auditing enforced. Rotation policy and admin revoke controls implemented.\n\n9. Per-region and Residency\n   - Support per-region deployment by automating provisioning of region-specific infra (DB, storage, realtime) when required. Evaluate Supabase's per-region capabilities; if insufficient, use cloud-managed Postgres instances for region-specific tenants.\n\n10. DB connection pooling and serverless constraints\n    - To avoid Postgres connection exhaustion with serverless functions, use PgBouncer or a connection proxy, or host critical API endpoints on long-lived managed Node services. Cache hot reads in Redis.\n\n---\n\n## Technology Stack\n\nFrontend\n- React + TypeScript\n- Chakra UI or Tailwind (WCAG AA target)\n- React Query (TanStack Query) for server state; Context for local state\n- E2E: Cypress\n- Build & Deploy: Vercel (preview deployments for PRs)\n\nBackend & Workers\n- Node.js + TypeScript REST API (Fastify recommended for performance) deployed on managed Node service for production-critical endpoints; non-critical endpoints can be serverless functions if connection pooling handled.\n- Background workers: Node.js workers using BullMQ (Redis) or cloud tasks depending on infra choice. Optimization microservice (optional) Python + OR-Tools for CP-SAT solver behind REST/gRPC.\n- AI Gateway service (Node/Python) sitting between application and LLM providers.\n\nDatabase & Storage\n- Primary DB: Postgres (Supabase for MVP or managed Postgres for per-region/per-tenant needs)\n- Storage: S3-compatible (Supabase Storage or S3). CDN (CloudFront/Cloudflare) for static assets.\n- Cache & queue: Redis (for caching, locks, and BullMQ) and/or managed alternatives.\n- Optional Search: Postgres tsvector for MVP; OpenSearch/Elastic in roadmap if richer search needed.\n\nIntegrations\n- Email: SendGrid / Postmark\n- Maps: Mapbox / Google Maps\n- Calendar: Google Calendar / Microsoft Graph (OAuth)\n- Observability: OpenTelemetry + Sentry + Prometheus/Grafana (or hosted monitoring)\n\nCI/CD & IaC\n- GitHub Actions for CI; restrict secret exposure in PRs\n- IaC: Terraform modules for infra provisioning (including per-tenant DBs/buckets)\n- Dependency scanning: Snyk or equivalent; supply-chain protections (pinned deps, SBOM)\n\nSecurity\n- Secrets Manager + KMS, SCA, pen testing pre-release, and defined incident response runbook.\n\n---\n\n## Database Design\n\nDesign principles\n- Normalize frequently queried entities (scenes, schedule_items) for performance and reporting.\n- Store full parsed JSON for audit/backup but keep scene-level relation rows for efficient queries and indexing.\n- Implement tsvector columns for full-text search on scripts/comments.\n- Soft-delete + archival/purge pipeline; immutable audit logs for financial/approval actions stored separately in append-only storage.\n\nPrimary tables (high level)\n- organizations (id, name, region, plan, settings, created_at)\n- users (id, org_id, name, email, role(s), last_active, mfa_enabled, status)\n- projects (id, org_id, title, timezone, start_date, end_date, status, version_token, created_by, created_at)\n- scripts (id, project_id, uploaded_by, file_url, file_type, version_number, parsed_json_id*, ai_summary_short, ai_summary_long, created_at)\n  - parsed_json stored in script_parses table (separate) to avoid large row bloat\n- scenes (id, script_id, scene_number, slugline, interior_exterior, day_night, page_estimate, estimated_minutes, sequence_order)\n- people (id, org_id, name, roles, rate_type, rate_amount, contact_info, availability_windows jsonb)\n- locations (id, org_id, name, address, latlng, capacity, booking_cost_estimate, booking_constraints)\n- schedules / shoot_days (id, project_id, date, location_id, call_time_utc, wrap_time_utc, notes, status, version_token)\n- schedule_assignments (id, schedule_id, person_id, role, time_on_set_estimate, locked_by, locked_until)\n- budgets & budget_items (id, project_id, category, description, currency, estimated_amount, committed_amount, actual_amount, change_history_id)\n- assets (id, project_id, storage_path, file_type, metadata jsonb, uploaded_by, current_version_id, protected_flag)\n- asset_versions (id, asset_id, storage_path, metadata, uploaded_at)\n- comments (id, org_id, entity_type, entity_id, author_id, body, rendered_body, created_at, resolved_flag)\n- approvals (id, org_id, entity_type, entity_id, requested_by, status, approver_ids, logs jsonb)\n- audit_logs (id, org_id, user_id, action_type, entity_ref, payload jsonb, created_at, immutable_hash)\n- notifications (id, user_id, org_id, type, payload, delivered_at, read_at)\n- ai_requests (id, org_id, user_id, request_type, input_hash, model_id, prompt_template_id, response, token_usage, cached boolean, created_at, status)\n- jobs (id, org_id, job_type, payload, status, attempts, result, created_at, last_updated)\n\nIndexes and search\n- Indexes on (org_id, project_id, created_at), (org_id, id) primary, and scenes: (script_id, scene_number).\n- tsvector columns for script text and comments; GIN indexes on jsonb where appropriate.\n- Materialized views for common dashboard aggregates and scheduled refresh.\n\nVersioning and retention\n- Scripts and assets: store full versions (asset_versions and script_parses). Retain last N versions by default (configurable per org).\n- Soft delete: boolean + deleted_at; separate archival retention and purge jobs per org.\n- Audit logs: append-only, immutable hashing, retained per policy.\n\nRow-Level Security & Authorization\n- Enforce org_id equality in policies for shared DB.\n- Protect high-sensitivity tables (budget_items, approvals) with stricter checks (role required).\n- DB policies must derive org_id from JWT claims (supabase.auth.claims) and not from user-supplied path params.\n\nNotes\n- Avoid storing large blobs in DB (store references to storage). Use small metadata and thumbnails in DB.\n\n---\n\n## Security Requirements\n\nHigh-level approach: defense-in-depth across auth, transport, data at rest, secrets, uploads, AI usage, and operations.\n\n1. Authentication & Session Management\n   - Use Supabase Auth or equivalent identity provider for user management, but enforce platform-level session controls.\n   - Token lifetimes:\n     - Access tokens: short-lived (<= 15 minutes)\n     - Refresh tokens: rotate on use, one-time-use pattern; expire after configurable window (e.g., 30 days).\n   - Session revocation:\n     - Store session metadata in a server-side session store (Redis) to enable immediate revocation on password reset, role change, or admin action.\n     - Admin APIs to revoke all sessions for a user or all org sessions.\n   - MFA:\n     - Support TOTP-based MFA (strongly recommended for Admin/Finance roles).\n\n2. Authorization & RLS\n   - Authorization enforced at API middleware and DB RLS policies (defense-in-depth).\n   - Always derive org_id and user identity from validated JWT claims on the server; ignore client-supplied org_id for access control.\n   - Central authorization middleware to enforce role-based permission checks consistent with a published Role-Permission Matrix (deliverable).\n   - Automated tests to assert no cross-org access.\n\n3. File Upload & Parsing Security\n   - Direct-to-storage signed uploads (no passing file data through API).\n   - Enforce file type by magic bytes + MIME; size limits; quota enforcement.\n   - Malware scanning on ingest; parsing and thumbnailing in isolated worker containers with resource caps.\n   - Sanitized previews; do not serve original file raw unless authorized.\n\n4. AI / LLM Safeguards\n   - PII handling:\n     - Default behavior: detect & redact sensitive PII before sending to external LLMs unless org explicitly opts in and contract permits.\n     - Provide per-org opt-in toggles and capture consent; support on-prem/private LLM integration for sensitive orgs.\n   - Prompt injection mitigation:\n     - Keep system prompts & templates server-side and separate from user content.\n     - Sanitize user content used in system-level prompts.\n   - Contractual protections:\n     - For customers requiring it, negotiate “no training” clauses with LLM providers and maintain contractual documentation.\n   - Audit trail:\n     - All AI calls logged with prompt_id, (redacted) prompt snippet, model_id, token usage, response hash & provenance info.\n   - Quotas:\n     - Enforce per-org daily compute budget caps and fail-safe backpressure if exceeded.\n\n5. API Abuse & Quotas\n   - Enforce per-user & per-org rate limits at API gateway.\n   - Heavy endpoints (optimize, estimate-cost) require async job submission and costing checks for high-cost requests.\n   - Admin controls to restrict heavy features per-org.\n\n6. Secrets & Keys\n   - Use a centralized secrets manager with KMS; do not store production secrets in plaintext environment vars or in DB unencrypted.\n   - OAuth refresh tokens stored encrypted in DB with envelope encryption; access limited to AI Gateway or integration worker processes.\n\n7. Network & Transport\n   - TLS everywhere for API/frontend/external calls.\n   - Least-privilege IAM roles for cloud resources and service accounts.\n\n8. Audit & Tamper Resistance\n   - Audit logs append-only; stored in separate, access-controlled location; include immutable hashes for tamper evidence.\n   - Retention and WORM policies configurable per org/contract.\n\n9. CI/CD & Supply Chain\n   - Restrict secrets in CI; disallow forks access to secrets.\n   - Pin critical dependencies where practical; implement SCA tooling and SBOM generation.\n\n10. Incident Response & Pen Testing\n   - Incident runbook, monthly backup restore testing, and periodic pen tests before public release.\n\n---\n\n## API Design\n\nPrinciples\n- RESTful JSON API, versioned at /api/v1/\n- All requests authenticated via short-lived access JWTs. Effective org_id derived from JWT.\n- Standardized error response envelope: { code, message, details }.\n- Use correlation_id for tracing across requests, jobs, and external services.\n- Use cursor-based pagination (recommended) for lists; define default and max page sizes.\n\nRouting and semantics\n- Resource paths include org scoping for clarity but server derives org from JWT; path orgId is validated to match JWT or ignored for routing (explicit validation enforced).\n- Mutating endpoints require version_token/ETag (optimistic concurrency). Provide 409 conflict responses with current representation for client reconciliation.\n- Heavy/long-running operations: asynchronous job pattern\n  - POST /orgs/:orgId/projects/:projectId/schedules/optimize → 202 + { jobId }.\n  - GET /jobs/:jobId → job status/result.\n- AI endpoints:\n  - POST /api/v1/ai/summarize-script → synchronous if small; includes provenance metadata in response header/body.\n  - POST /api/v1/ai/optimize-schedule → asynchronous (job accepted) if expected to be expensive.\n  - All AI responses include metadata: model_used, prompt_template_id, prompt_hash (redacted), generated_at, token_usage, cached boolean.\n\nAuthentication & Session\n- POST /auth/login → returns access_token, refresh_token (rotating)\n- POST /auth/refresh → uses one-time refresh token; new refresh token issued.\n- POST /auth/logout → revokes session server-side.\n- Admin endpoint: POST /admin/users/:id/revoke-sessions\n\nPagination & Filtering\n- Use cursor pagination: ?page_size=50&cursor=<opaque_cursor>\n- Filtering & sorting by canonical fields (e.g., ?sort=created_at:desc&filter[role]=Actor)\n- Documented in OpenAPI.\n\nError Patterns & Rate Limit Headers\n- Consistent errors: 400/401/403/404/409/429/500.\n- Include rate-limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset).\n\nRealtime API\n- WebSocket or provider channels (Supabase Realtime / Ably) for channels: schedules, comments, notifications, presence.\n- Token-based auth for realtime with limited TTL.\n\nKey endpoints (representative)\n- Auth: /auth/signup, /auth/login, /auth/refresh, /auth/logout, /users/me\n- Organizations: GET /orgs/:orgId, PATCH /orgs/:orgId/settings\n- Projects: POST/GET/PATCH /orgs/:orgId/projects\n- Scripts: POST (upload -> client obtains signed upload URL & then triggers parse job), GET script, GET versions, POST /ai-summarize\n- People: CRUD /orgs/:orgId/people (bulk import endpoint)\n- Schedules: CRUD schedules; POST /schedules/optimize (async), GET /schedules/:id/conflicts\n- Budgets: CRUD budgets & items; POST /budgets/estimate (async job with deterministic fallback)\n- Assets: POST returns upload URL, then process job; GET preview; GET versions\n- Comments & Approvals: POST /comments, GET /entities/:id/comments, POST /approvals, PATCH /approvals/:id\n- Notifications: GET /users/:id/notifications, POST /notifications/mark-read\n- AI: unified /api/v1/ai/* endpoints with enforced quotas\n- Jobs: GET /jobs/:id\n\nOpenAPI & Contract Testing\n- Full OpenAPI spec required; CI includes contract tests and OpenAPI validation.\n\nAPI Docs & SDKs\n- Provide API docs and language-neutral SDKs or TypeScript client as deliverables for developer experience.\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\nTesting principle: automated, comprehensive tests across layers, including failure and security modes.\n\nTest suites\n- Unit tests: business logic, parsers, deterministics (Jest); high coverage on critical modules (parsing, cost calculator, authorization middleware).\n- Integration tests: DB migrations, RLS policies, API endpoints (using test secrets & sample datasets).\n- End-to-end tests: Cypress for core flows (project creation, script upload & parse, schedule create & optimize, approval flow).\n- Contract tests: OpenAPI-based contract validations.\n- AI evaluation tests:\n  - Regression tests for LLM outputs on a synthetic dataset (expected summaries, estimated budgets).\n  - Prompt-response validation, hallucination rate tracking on test dataset, and performance thresholds.\n- Security tests:\n  - SCA (Snyk), static code analysis, DAST scans, and scheduled pen testing.\n  - RLS & RBAC integration tests (positive/negative access verification).\n- Performance & Load:\n  - k6 or Artillery load tests for API targeting median latency goals and concurrency targets.\n  - Stress tests for workers and AI gateway; include quotas enforcement tests.\n- Fault injection & chaos:\n  - Simulate external service outages (LLM, email, maps) and verify graceful degradation/fallbacks.\n- Observability & restore tests:\n  - Monthly backup & restore verification (automated test in staging).\n- Parser robustness:\n  - Test suite with diverse script formats (malformed PDFs, different encodings, missing sluglines).\n- Accessibility:\n  - Automated axe checks and manual WCAG AA spot checks.\n\nQA acceptance tests\n- Include timezone & DST tests (see QA findings) for schedule correctness across timezones.\n- Concurrency tests for schedule editing (simulate concurrent edits & verify conflict resolution UX).\n\nTest data & staging\n- Seed staging with synthetic dataset (scripts, roster, schedules) for reproducible AI tests and QA.\n\nCI pipeline\n- Pre-merge: lint, typecheck, unit tests\n- Merge: integration tests, contract tests, E2E smoke\n- Post-merge deploy to staging with smoke tests and canary metrics\n- Manual promotion to production with curated smoke tests\n\n---\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\nRefined, measurable acceptance targets that address functional and non-functional concerns.\n\nFunctional\n1. Project creation\n   - Create & view a project; appears in dashboard. (Automated functional test)\n\n2. Script upload & summarization\n   - Upload a script <=20MB via signed URL. Parse job completes within 2 minutes for typical files and stores parsed scenes.\n   - AI summary short (2–3 sentences) and long (paragraph) returned within 15s for typical prompts or via async job completion. Summaries include provenance metadata.\n\n3. People management\n   - Create/import 10 people, assign to scenes; availability editable.\n\n4. Schedules & optimization\n   - Create a 5-day schedule; optimization job returns a viable alternative respecting availability and reduces location moves by >10% on test dataset (heuristic).\n   - Conflict detection reliably identifies overlapping person assignments and reports them.\n\n5. Budgeting & cost estimation\n   - Create budget & line items; deterministic cost estimator provides per-day and total estimates. AI-assisted estimation available with explicit provenance and opt-in for external LLM usage.\n\n6. Assets & versioning\n   - Upload asset via signed URL, create version, retrieve older versions and preview thumbnails.\n\n7. Collaboration & approvals\n   - Post comment; in-app notification delivered within target SLO and email queued for delivery. Approval triggers audit log entry.\n\n8. Multi-tenant isolation & auth\n   - RLS and API tests pass showing users cannot access other org data.\n   - Session revocation works within 30s of admin action.\n\nNon-functional & operational\n9. Availability & performance\n   - Target SLO: 99.9% uptime for core UI & API.\n   - Standard API median latency < 300ms under nominal load; AI endpoints handled separately (typical 3–15s).\n   - Realtime in-session update propagation < 2s for typical updates.\n\n10. Backups & recovery\n    - RPO <= 24 hours and RTO for critical services < 4 hours (production incident runbook meets these targets).\n    - Monthly restore test passes for database & storage.\n\n11. Observability & alerting\n    - Errors captured in Sentry; critical metric alerts configured for error rates, queue backlogs, AI cost runaway.\n\n12. Security & compliance\n    - Pen test finding remediation completed before public release.\n    - Audit and DSR workflows validated in QA environment.\n\n13. Timezone handling\n    - All stored timestamps in UTC; per-project timezone displayed and respected in UIs & calendar sync; DST transitions handled per specified behavior tests.\n\n14. Testing coverage\n    - Unit/integration/contract + E2E critical flows passing in CI with coverage thresholds for critical modules.\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Constraints and Operational Requirements\n\n1. Serverless limitations\n   - Do not perform large uploads or heavy CPU-bound parsing in serverless functions due to timeouts and ephemeral disk limits. Use signed uploads + workers.\n\n2. Job & Worker SLAs\n   - Asynchronous jobs have SLOs: typical parse job < 2 minutes; optimization jobs depending on solver complexity with queued capacity; job visibility & DLQ for failures.\n\n3. Cost & Quota Controls for AI\n   - Enforce per-org compute budgets and per-request token limits. Provide usage dashboard and alerts for org admins.\n\n4. Secrets & Credential Rotation\n   - Centralized secrets manager required; CI configured to avoid exposing secrets in logs or PRs.\n\n5. Per-region automation\n   - Automate ability to provision per-region DB and storage for contractual data residency requirements. Document cost & operational overhead.\n\n6. API Gateway & Scaling\n   - Front API should support rate limiting, request throttling, and quota responses. Heavy endpoints should prefer async job pattern.\n\n7. Data retention & purge\n   - Implement retention configurations per org; archival & purge jobs with audit logging. For privileged delete requests, run documented erase workflow and coordinate with backups policy.\n\n8. Developer Experience\n   - Provide TypeScript SDK, OpenAPI docs, local dev environment seed scripts and clear onboarding README. Encourage feature toggles for LLM features during dev/test.\n\n9. Compliance & Legal\n   - Maintain contractual templates for LLM providers concerning data usage; offer opt-out/in per org for data-sending to external LLM providers.\n\n10. Deliverables & Operational Artefacts\n    - Role & Permission Matrix (explicit mapping)\n    - OpenAPI spec + contract tests\n    - ERD and schema migrations\n    - Prompt templates & AI governance docs\n    - Monitoring dashboards, runbooks (backup/restore, incident), and security posture reports\n    - Test dataset & CI-configured test suites\n\n---\n\nAppendices / Next Steps\n- Finalize Role & Permission Matrix and publish as canonical document for API & DB policy enforcement.\n- Produce ERD and full OpenAPI spec; include schema-level RLS policies in migration scripts.\n- Implement Org Provisioner IaC modules for per-tenant provisioning and include tests for tenant lifecycle.\n- Build AI Gateway with per-org quota & provenance before enabling LLM-based features for production tenants.\n- Implement RLS policy tests and CI gating to prevent misconfiguration.\n- Start with shared-DB default but validate and automate per-tenant DB provisioning for early enterprise customers requiring stronger guarantees.\n\nThis final specification addresses the architecture, security, and QA concerns while preserving the product goals. It describes safe defaults, operational paths for stronger isolation/residency, and the mechanisms needed to meet the MVP acceptance criteria with an emphasis on reliability and security."